editorNotes: Bastiodon is the sheer definition of bulk. It has two double weaknesses to crack it, and its abysmal pacing and pressure can leave it exposed in bad situations. That said, Bastiodon's playstyle is not for the faint of heart. Good predictions and commitment to alignment are keys for success.

Empoleon is among the standout Hydro Cannon users of the format thanks to its incredible pacing and Steel typing. It has solidified itself as a defining player in the meta, especially alongside its core partner, Altaria. Its primary downsides are its lower stat product and its struggles into other Water types.

It has solidified itself as a defining player in the meta, especially alongside its core partner, Altaria. Its primary downsides are its lower stat product and its struggles into other Water types.

Cradily continues to be a landmark presence in the format. Its Rock Tomb debuff augments its already bulky stats. That said, it's not without drawbacks. Its moderate pacing also incentivizes it to shield early. Rising Steel types and a wider variety of Ghost also pose a challenge.

Charjabug boasts decent stats and neutral play, which are hard to find among other Electric types. Its Bug typing softens its matchups against Ground types, and X-Scissor is highly valuable against Grass. Crunch is an option to hit back against the meta's prominent Ghosts.

Amid stiff competition between Fairy types, Florges has risen as a top choice alongside Azumarill and Wigglytuff. It is the most energy-oriented of the three, and its mix of coverage and stat effects give it play into the meta's top Water and Ground types. However, it's more awkward into Altaria than its alternatives.

Murkrow is an aggressive, fast-paced alternative to Galarian Moltres, and is a blast to play. As its rankings indicate, it thrives when it has energy advantage, and this high skill ceiling has led to its rising competitive success. However, Murkrow depends much more on shields and team support. The regular version is generally preferred over the Shadow to balance its offensive power with just enough bulk to stay viable.

Aegislash now has the ability to stack both of its Charged Attacks, increasing the viability of its glassy Blade Forme. However, it has yet to prove itself in competitive play, especially since its prohibitive cost reduces its play rate. Time will tell if these buffs can overcome its cumbersome mechanics.

Spiritomb sees far less play than its counterpart, Sableye. Its pacing is considerably slow in a meta that is growing ever faster. In particular, this means it can't take full advantage of Rock Tomb's debuffs.

The sims don't always use Chilling Water optimally, so Alolan Ninetales should perform better in some head to head matchups than indicated. Chilling Water is a sidegrade, if not a slight improvement which gives Alolan Ninetales coverage against Fire and broader technical play.

Furret has assumed the neutral Normal-type role in place of predecessors like Dunsparce and Lickitung. While it lacks their bulk, its deceptive offenses, valuable Grass coverage, and sheer dominance against Ghosts make it a strong centerpiece in the meta. Fighting type counters are scarce, so its main threats are Steel and Fairy.

Shadow Talonflame takes its sweeper role to even scarier heights. It occupies a middle ground between regular Talonflame and Shadow Charizard, with a greater focus on Fast Attack pressure and Attack boosts. The simulations more readily capture its pitfalls, where it's harshly punished by Rock, Water, and Electric.

Blastoise is the bulkiest Hydro Cannon user and can augment this even further with Skull Bash. With an excellent balance of stats, power, and speed, it occupies a small but strong spot in the metagame.

Shadow Scizor brings incredible Fast Attack pressure into the meta, especially against Cradily. Since Fire types are relatively rare, Scizor has seen more open play. Scizor's ability to deal damage is just as polarizing as its inability to take damage. Good prediction skills, careful piloting, and a dose of luck all help its competitive success.

Despite its double weakness to Ice, Altaria is rising as a top meta contender. Its increased flexibility with Flamethrower gives it coverage against Steel types, and its defensive typing remains one of the best to counter Water and Ground types like Gastrodon.

Walrein has a notable competitive past, but hasn't found a way to crack the current metagame. Its time may come again, but faces too much competition against rival Water types, including its pre-evolution, Sealeo.

Lapras has a long competitive history, but is currently on its way out of the metagame. It's a poster child for bulky Water types and neutral play. Recent shifts have left it without a clear role, and it now faces stiff competition among Water/Ice types.

Lapras has a long competitive history, but is currently on its way out of the metagame. It's a poster child for bulky Water types and neutral play. Recent shifts have left it without a clear role as it lacks decisive matchups in the meta.

Altaria is the only Dragon to see widespread play in the current meta, and Goodra presents few advantages over it. Its middling stats and non-STAB attacks give it a soft matchup profile that allows it to play as a corebreaker, but it it lacks the strength as a generalist to truly succeed.

Hydreigon has the typing to corebreak current meta threats. However, its double weakness to Fairy and glassy stats pose severe challenges to its success. Expert hands may be required to pilot this one over more established picks like Guzzlord or Zweilous.

Azumarill has withstood the test of time and remains one of Great League's most prominent mascots. It owes this to its extreme bulk and excellent defensive typing. Azumarill's main drawback is its pacing, which leaves it outsped by the format's more aggressive picks. Empoleon and Jellicent are posing new threats to its spot.

Once a dreaded Great League staple, Lickitung is viable but outclassed by other Normal types, including its evolution, Lickilicky. Lickitung has high bulk but lacks the speed and power to compete in a meta that is becoming increasingly faster.
Carbink's bulk and Fairy typing aren't enough to carry it to meta relevancy. It rarely sees play over its Steel-type counterpart, Bastiodon, and shares many similar pitfalls with fewer resistances.

Galarian Corsola has fallen out of favor in the current meta as rival Ghost types cannibalize its role. Normal type counters like Wigglytuff and Furret are also becoming more prevalent. A high rank Galarian Corsola has better neutral matchups than one with hatch IV's, so look to save your resources for the right one.
Clefable is finally finding a place in the metagame with its powerful Charged Attack options. Meteor Mash in particular gives it play into other Fairies and an out against Cradily.

Similar to Mandibuzz, Umbreon has all the bulk in the world, but has seen little consideration in the current meta. Fairy is an omnipresent threat, and other Dark types provide more convincing matchup profiles.

Clodsire has regained a strong position in the metagame despite Mud Slap users vying for its Ground role. Its flexible offenses and great defenses make it a stellar generalist. Its main drawbacks are its low Fast Attack pressure and its weaknesses to Ground, Ice, and Water.

Forretress is falling behind in the meta as other Steel types threaten to wall it. Some may find its moveset slow and awkward. While it has a strong competitive history, watch out for increasing sources of Fire damage.

Despite stiff competition, Marowak has regained ground and remains one of the meta's top threats. The Shadow variant is strongly preferred, as its Fast Attack pressure can bulldoze through even negative matchups.

Marowak is losing ground in the meta, with Gastrodon being preferred for its more neutral typing profile. The Shadow variant is strongly preferred, as its Fast Attack pressure can bulldoze through even negative matchups.

Mandibuzz has sheer bulk on its side, but has failed to break back into the meta in a meaningful way. Its new moveset is walled by rival Dark types, and it struggles significantly against dominant Fairies.

Galarian Moltres is a top Flying type in competitive play thanks to its strong matchups against meta defining Ground and Ghost types. It often finds significant neutral play. Its stats are more tempered than its predecessor, Mandibuzz, so it does have to watch for Ice or Rock coverage.

Gastrodon is the premier Ground type. With a solitary weakness to Grass, it's a flexible cornerstone for team building and a defining piece of the metagame. Its main counters are Flying types, in particularly those that resist its Normal or Water-type Charged Attacks.

Outside of the simulations, Talonflame is one of the format's most dangerous sweepers. It shines with a shield advantage. Its 5-turn Fast Attack gives it a steep learning curve, difficult to master and exploitable by skilled opponents. However, these haven't deterred its high usage.

Jellicent was a strong Pokemon before, and with the buff to Shadow Ball, it now has all the makings of a top meta Pokemon. Excellent stats, defensive typing, pacing, and power make Jellicent a key pick going forward.

Diggersby has fallen off in the format, overtaken by stronger Ground types and stronger Normal types. Notably, it lacks the Fast Attack pressure of Mud Slap, which has become a defining feature of the format. Its bulk still keeps it plenty competitive.
Diggersby has fallen off in the format, overtaken by stronger Ground types and stronger Normal types. The Shadow variant rarely ever sees play, since its bulk is its strongest asset.
Guzzlord is preferred over Zweilous with its slightly better stats and Poison coverage into Fairy counters.
Guzzlord is preferred over Zweilous with its slightly better stats and Poison coverage into Fairy counters.

Sealeo has the offenses and pacing to make for a neutral, energy-oriented threat like Walrein before it. However, it hasn't made much headway in the metagame thus far, so its competitive potential remains to be proven.

True to its name, Shadow Steelix is among the standout Steel types in the format. Thunder Fang plus debuffing attacks give it a unique role. The Shadow boost helps make up for its lack of STAB, but it still struggles with its minimal shield pressure and closing power. Look to pair it with strong offensive pressure and Pokemon that can capitalize on alignment.
Shadow Steelix is typically preferred over the regular variant for additional Fast Attack pressure and the boost to its non-STAB attacks.

Regidrago packs a powerful signature attack and a spammy neutral option in Vise Grip. Its stats leave something to be desired, and it is more one-dimensional than other Dragon options. It is largely unproven in competition.

Corviknight's excellent stats and typing make it highly rated in simulations and harken back to the heydays of Skarmory. While Corviknight has a more neutral matchup profile, this is both a positive and a negative, as Corviknight can struggle through matchups which appear to be intuitive wins. One of Corviknight's biggest criticisms is its weak offenses, which make Corviknight better at absorbing damage than dealing it.

Tinkaton is strong in a vacuum, with excellent stats, energy generation, and one of the best typings in the game. Its Steel typing, however, is more of a hinderance with the prominence of Ground in the current meta. Bulldoze is also not convincing enough of a coverage move to shore up its matchups. It takes a backseat to more well rounded Fairy types.

Araquanid has a notable competitive history, but it's marred by inconsistency and inflexibility. It relies on Bubble Beam debuffs to chew through matchups, giving it an awkward and sluggish playstyle.
